P4 High IO Incident Lab - Cleaned Terminal Summary

=== P4 HIGH IO INCIDENT START ===
Date: Mon Mar 9 03:40:06 AM PDT 2026

1. Created the project directory and entered it:

mkdir ~/P4-High-IO-Lab
cd ~/P4-High-IO-Lab

2. Checked baseline disk I/O performance:

iostat -x 1 4

Observation:
System was mostly idle during the baseline check.
Initial disk utilization on /dev/sda was low, around 9–10%.
CPU iowait was also low.

3. Started extended I/O monitoring:

iostat -x 1

4. During the high I/O condition, the following indicators were observed on /dev/sda:

- %util repeatedly increased to approximately 93%–99%
- %iowait increased significantly, reaching approximately 62%–94%
- write throughput (wkB/s) increased substantially
- the system spent a large portion of CPU time waiting on disk I/O

Example observations:
- %util = 99.20%, %iowait = 62.83%
- %util = 98.20%, %iowait = 79.12%
- %util = 97.80%, %iowait = 84.80%
- %util = 98.02%, %iowait = 93.92%
- %util = 97.40%, %iowait = 89.07%
- %util = 93.50%, %iowait = 55.15%

This confirmed a sustained high disk I/O condition.

5. Investigated running fio processes:

ps aux | grep fio

Result:
Two fio-related processes were identified:

PID 7003
PID 7007

Command observed:
fio --name=high-io-test --filename=fiotestfile --size=20G --rw=write --bs=1M --iodepth=16 --runtime=600 --time_based

6. Stopped the I/O workload:

kill 7003
kill 7007

Result:
One process terminated successfully.
The second process had already exited by the time the kill command was issued.

7. Verified recovery after stopping the workload:

iostat -x 1 2

Observation:
Disk activity returned to near zero.
CPU idle returned to approximately 99%.
Disk utilization on /dev/sda dropped back to 0%.
This confirmed that the high I/O condition had ended.

=== P4 HIGH IO INCIDENT END ===
Date: Mon Mar 9 03:52:54 AM PDT 2026

Summary:
This lab simulated a high disk I/O incident using fio and monitored the system with iostat. During the incident, disk utilization on /dev/sda rose close to 100% and CPU iowait became very high, indicating a disk bottleneck. The source of the I/O load was identified with ps aux | grep fio, and the issue was resolved by terminating the fio process. Final verification confirmed that disk utilization and iowait returned to normal.
